Staff Notes: Findings from EBMUD’s annual Water Supply Availability and Deficiency Report showed supplies will be insufficient to meet demand and consequently, on April 27, 2021, the Board of Directors made a Declaration that current and projected conditions warranted triggering a Drought Stage 1 as defined in EBMUD’s 2020 Water Shortage Contingency Plan (Attachment 1 of the 2020 UWMP). As the severity the drought continued into spring of 2022 and with unknown uncertainty for the coming year of hydrologic conditions or dry year supplemental supply availability, on April 26, 2022, the Board of Directors made a Declaration that current and projected conditions warranted triggering a Drought Stage 2 as defined in EBMUD’s 2020 Water Shortage Contingency Plan (Attachment 1 of the 2020 UWMP). Table W-5 in the Attachment 1 outlines the response actions to take depending upon severity of the drought.    Subsequently declaration of Drought Stage 2, on May 10, 2022, the Board of Directors made a Declaration to implement Drought Stage 2 surcharges. The Drought Surcharges is to be imposed and collected on each unit of potable water delivered on or after July 1, 2022 at the rate of eight percent (8%) of the Water Flow Charge for Water Delivered.

Staff Notes: The City of Oceanside and its wholesale water agency, San Diego County Water Authority, have made many significant investments in both water use efficiency and reliable water supplies to improve the water resiliency in the region. Water use efficiency measures include robust regional rebate programs for water-saving devices and turf removal as well as workshops and messaging to give residents and businesses the tools they need to become WaterSmart. In response to the Governor's Emergency Declaration; the City of Oceanside initiated Level 2 Drought Actions of our Water Shortage Contingency Plan. Through careful planning and resource management, our Drought Risk Assessment shows the San Diego region will have adequate water supplies under 5 years of drought conditions. In December 2021, the City of Oceanside's Pure Water Oceanside, an indirect potable reuse project, began operating and is the first fully operational IPR project in the County. The City is also expanding our recycled water system. With the implementation of these two projects, during specific times of the year, the City of Oceanside will be able to reuse all of its wastewater. In addition, the City is also in the implementation phase of upgrading all meters to AMI meters. The City will be fully AMI in 2023. The City of Oceanside continued its efforts to promote conservation with increased outreach regarding the Governor's order to reduce water use by 15%, water conservation resources, and educational material through the City's website, social media, TV, and newsletters

Hose washing of sidewalks, walkways, driveways, parking areas, hardscapes, or other paved surfaces shall be prohibited.         2. No water shall be used to clean, fill or maintain levels in decorative fountains, or other similar aesthetic structures unless such water is part of a recycling system.         4.     Watering in a manner that causes runoff from landscaped areas into adjoining streets, sidewalks, or other paved areas, or watering within forty-eight hours after measurable precipitation shall be prohibited.         5.     Irrigating ornamental turf on public street medians shall be prohibited.
